<table bgcolor="#FFFFFF" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td width="10"><img width="10" height="1" src="images/space.gif" alt=""></td><td width="100%"><!-- spacer -->

<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" bgcolor="#555576"  width="100%" align="center"><tr><td>
<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="1" border="0"  width="100%">
<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#F1F1F1" width="175" valign="top" nowrap>
	<a name="post144890"></a>
	
	<font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" ><b>Riverdane</b></font><br>
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" >Forum Wizard</font><br>
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" ></font><br>
	<p>
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" >Server: Vazaelle<br>
	Guild: <br>
	<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=&resize=true" target=_blank>Magelo Profile</a><br>
	</font></td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#F1F1F1" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" > <b></b></font>
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" >"This place hasn't changed," Rocsalt remarked, settling down in his old chair at the chessboard. Camille took a seat opposite him in River's old chair. Talvarien and Grelin were still outside foraging up some vegetables from the garden.<br />
<br />
Roc was staring at the chessboard. The pieces had dust gathered on them, the black horsemen and pikemen almost as white as the opposing pieces. They were scattered across the board, not lined up neat they way they would at the beginning of a game.<br />
<br />
"You never cleaned this up." Roc commented, gesturing to the game. Camille just shook her head. "See this?" Roc continued, pointing to the white Lady piece. He reached out and slid it diagonally across the white squares, cleaning a straight line behind the piece through the dust as he did. He brought it to rest five squares away. Then he reached out and tipped the black King onto its side. It hit the marble board with a clunk. Roc leaned back.<br />
<br />
"Checkmate." Roc said quietly. "I had him that night, if he didn't go to Velks..."<br />
<br />
"I wish you had won." Camille answered, staring at the Black king on its side. The king regarded her mutely from its fallen spot on the game board, crown still on its head, but beaten, on its side, its time and place in the game over. Game over.<br />
<br />
Roc laughed suddenly. "Damned River. You know what Logik used to hate? We'd be in Western Waste, and I'd be pulling in one of the big lizards, and as soon as I would come up over that last snowbank River would turn to them on that horse of his and bark 'If you aren't STANDING when the dragon comes, you have effectively pinned a sign to your forehead that says EAT ME'...boy, Logik used to get so insulted with that, like Riv thought we were all noobs working the front of Crushbone."<br />
<br />
Camille smiled at Roc's imitation. "He just wanted to make sure everyone got home alive."<br />
<br />
"Aye, I tried to explain that to Logik, that he wanted to make sure no one was sleeping, but you know Logik, you can take the barbarian out of Halas, but you can't take the Halas out of the barbarian."<br />
<br />
"Well, River certainly has found ways even in death of keeping me from sleeping..." she commented, but then noticed Rocsalt's eyes had drifted to the corner. Two large bowls sat in the corner, handlettered. The one on the right spelled out some letters in iksar and then, in common underneath, 'Warmblood', Zullie's wolf's feed dish. And the other, written in oversized lettering and an inexperienced hand, simply said 'Fang'.<br />
<br />
"When do we stop mourning the dead?" Camille asked sadly.<br />
<br />
"When we join them." Rocsalt replied. And then he burst out into a fit of coughing.<br />
<br />
"Are you alright?" Camille asked, startled. She had dealt with coughs before, River was always coughing to wake the dead after strenuous raids, with the way he smoked, but this was deeper, harsher.<br />
<br />
"Aye," Roc said, waving her off as she stood. He got his cough under control. "Something I picked up in Luclin while I ran around. A weird mushroom exploded in my face and I got a breathful of spores or something..."<br />
<br />
"Sorry no mushrooms." Talvarien said, coming in with Grelin, both carrying a small bushel each of fresh vegetables. But I did get celery, onions, lots and lots of lettuce, radishes, carrots...."<br />
<br />
"Tomatoes." Grelin added, wetting his lips.<br />
<br />
"Ugh, yeah tomatoes." Talvarien said, pulling down a large bowl and emptying the bushel onto the counter. "I hate tomatoes. Ok ok, the tomato is Quarken." He rolled it out into the pile of lettuce. "And Roc, you are the lettuce, and these here are the rest of the bar and GET HIM ROC DON'T LET HIM GET US!" Talvarien started tossing everything rapidly into the bowl and the shook the bowl furiously. "TOSS HIM ROC! TOSS HIM!" Camille just shook her head with a smile. Roc stared openly at the deranged ranger. "Oh nooooo!" Talv cried, as a piece of lettuce flew out of the bowl. "The Roc is out of the ring! Don't worry Roc, Talv the Knife will get him!" He began chopping furiously at the tomato with a parring knife. "Die tomato! Talv the Knife will slice you up with dual epics! A TOMATO IS SLOWED WITH RANJA POWER!"<br />
<br />
Grelin watched Talv's antics with a grin on his face. "Crazy." he said.<br />
<br />
"Shhh, you." Talvarien said, still slicing the tomato. "You're a carrot. Since when do carrots talk?"<br />
<br />
Camille motioned Roc over to the counter. "When you're done tanking dinner," she said to Talv, "I should fill Roc in on what's been going on around here and tell you what I found out."<br />
<br />
"Oh yeah." Talv said, slowing down his chopping. "Ranja.... down...." he said with a gasp. Then he pointed to the tomato. "You may have won today, Tomato, but....I'll be back."<br />
<br />
And then Camille began with her first dream and caught them up to Katarin's story, a twinge of guilt at so soon breaking her promise to the bard, but trusting the three as she would her own husband. And the night went on, Talvarien's half-tossed salad forgotten.</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p></p>
