<table bgcolor="#FFFFFF" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td width="10"><img width="10" height="1" src="images/space.gif" alt=""></td><td width="100%"><!-- spacer -->

<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" bgcolor="#555576"  width="100%" align="center"><tr><td>
<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="1" border="0"  width="100%">
<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#F1F1F1" width="175" valign="top" nowrap>
	<a name="post145274"></a>
	
	<font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" ><b>Riverdane</b></font><br>
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" >Forum Wizard</font><br>
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" ></font><br>
	<p>
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" >Server: Vazaelle<br>
	Guild: <br>
	<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=&resize=true" target=_blank>Magelo Profile</a><br>
	</font></td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#F1F1F1" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" > <b></b></font>
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" >And onward they rode...<br />
<br />
"Hands where I can see them!" Sergeant Slate barked, levelling his crossbow at the dark elf as he attempted to slip across East Commons to the Nektulos border. The elf cursed his luck and lifted his hands high in the air.<br />
<br />
"I'm just trying to get home." the teir'dal said in broken common. "I wasn't disturbing anyth..."<br />
<br />
"Well, today's your lucky day." Slate said smugly, "Because I'm in a good mood. Safe passage across the commons will only cost you what you have in your pockets." The dark elf cursed quietly in his native tongue. "Andddd," Slate continued, "I don't know what you just called me, you piece of trash, but that will cost you your boots as well. Now, off with them!"<br />
<br />
The dark elf decided silence was the best answer, and began to bend down to unlace his boots, when the sound of pounding hooves reached his ears. Both he and Slate turned in the direction of the noise.<br />
<br />
Bearing down on them, like a roaring river, came a black horse, flames flying out from its hooves as it thundered across the path. On its back was a beautiful woman with golden hair, gripping onto the horse's mane, bearing a dangerous toothedged sword. She rode with no saddle, knees up near the horses shoulders, squeezing the horse tight as she held on. She was dressed in a slight white dress, barefoot. They were a vision of Rallos' warrior riders, death incarnate riding in the moonlight. Slate gaped as she passed by without even glancing at them.<br />
<br />
"What in hells..." he murmured, as she passed him at a speed unlike any gallop he had ever witnessed. But just like that, the horse and rider were gone, marked only by a cloud of dust behind them.<br />
<br />
Slate blinked and turned back to his prisoner. "Did you see tha..."<br />
<br />
But the darkelf was gone.<br />
<br />
And onward they rode....<br />
<br />
In West Commons, Guards Valon and Colin played checkers inside the small hut attached to the toll booth. It was how every night usually ended since they pissed off Sir Lucan and wound up with one of the crappiest details of the Freeport Militia. At that time of night, the toll road got very little traffic. So on they went, jump jump jump with the game, until the sound of hooves hitting the paved road reached their ears.<br />
<br />
"Someone riding this late at night?" Colin asked, eyebrow raised.<br />
<br />
"I'll get it." Valon offered. "And I know where the pieces are, Colin, so don't think of cheating me." And out he went.<br />
<br />
The figure was still a bit in the distance, a lone person on horseback, moving toward the tollbooth with alarming speed.<br />
<br />
"Halt, in the name of the Freeport Militia. Use of this road is regulated to a toll." he called out, as usual.<br />
<br />
The rider showed no sign of slowing.<br />
<br />
"Halt! In the name of the Freeport Militia!" he called louder. Colin, hearing Valon repeat himself, came out to gape at the rider, who was not reining in the horse even in the slightest.<br />
<br />
"He said Halt, in the name of the..." Colin yelled out.<br />
<br />
"HALT! IN THE NAME OF...!" Valon screamed, waving his arms back and forth as the two stood in amazement as the horse bore down on them. Now it was close enough to see the flames licking the hooves of the horse, the fire shooting from its nostrils, the red hellfire in its eyes, and the wicked sword held by its ghostly rider.<br />
<br />
"Mother of Rallos..." Colin murmured, as his legs buckled. "LOOK OUT!"<br />
<br />
But Valon was moving without the warning. Colin dived left, Valon right, as the horse hit the toll gate full across its broad chest. It didn't even lose one step. The board that made the gate snapped off its swing, splintering and flipping a good distance away, almost taking off Colin's head as it sailed over him. Valon was getting to his feet, watching the rider disappear to a tiny dot in the distance.<br />
<br />
"Lucan is going to be...upset." Colin mentioned, looking at the destroyed toll gate.<br />
<br />
And onward they rode....<br />
<br />
"Do the Shralok orcs know what to do?" General V'Ghera asked, without looking up from his map of Highpass Hold as he scoured his papers in the burnt out cabin that posed as his headquarters in the Kithicor Forest. Luclin's sparce light would make the maps hard to read for a human, but the General's teir'dal eyes picked out every detail clearly.<br />
<br />
"Aye," Advisor C'zatl answered, nodding in the darkness. "On my order they'll meet with the orcs in the pass and sweep past the Keep, drawing the front guards to the west, and we'll be able to move in from the east."<br />
<br />
"Good good." V'Ghera murmured. "And the Pickclaw goblins?"<br />
<br />
"Ready to rise up and move into the upper Keep on my call." War Priestess T'zan said, licking her lips absently.<br />
<br />
"Q'ioul, the asslings...will they assist if they get word? Or...?"<br />
<br />
"All asleep in Rivervale, after a little taste of tainted jumjum." Coercer Q'ioul smiled. "Should we hit them after, take the halfling city?"<br />
<br />
General V'ghera regarded her for a moment, and then a smile broke across his dark face. "But...why?" he asked. And laughed nastily, as his entourage joined in heartily. Why indeed would anyone want to occupy Rivervale....<br />
<br />
"Sir?" Adjutant D'kan said suddenly, listening. "Do you hear somethi..."<br />
<br />
Suddenly, sweeping through their midst, a black stallion bearing a blonde rider charged through their midst, papers scattering with the wind from their passage. One of the horse's flaming hooves came down on the maps, and fire greedily began to consume them. And then, they were gone as fast as they came.<br />
<br />
General V'ghera stared after the horse and rider, as Adjutant D'kan stomped on the burning maps, putting out the flames.<br />
<br />
And onward they rode...<br />
<br />
"Rider in the pass!" came the frantic shout. Captain Orben ran from his post on the west watch, and peered over the wall high above the lower pass. He arrived just in time to see the back flanks of a horse disappear around a corner, and a wisp of golden hair.<br />
<br />
He frowned. "This bodes ill." he said to Renlor, one of the volunteers who watched the pass with the guards. "Send word through the Pass to double the security at the east and west entrances. Something odd is in the air tonight."<br />
<br />
Volunteer Renlor nodded briefly and was gone, while Captain Orben lit his pipe distractedly, eyes intent on the west pass. <br />
<br />
And onward they rode....<br />
<br />
Down the long twisting road from Highpass, Brimstone dangerously close to the edge, Camille's fingers feeling permanently twisted into a grip, as she squeezed her aching legs to the horse's neck and tried to stay balanced with one hand holding Reaver. She would jump off the speeding horse to her death before losing her husband's sword on what was becoming a nightmare journey across Antonica. Her body screamed in protest with each jarring step, while Brimstone dragged her unwillingly across the rushing landscape.<br />
<br />
Across East Karana they galloped, toward the wooden bridge that crossed the river into North Karana. Broon blinked his one cyclopean eye in disbelief as the firey horse and scantily clad rider flew by him like an arrow.<br />
<br />
Into North Karana, past the gypsy camp and guard tower, faster, faster, grffins steering clear of the rider as she was rushed across the plains, leaving small clumps of burning brush behind her, where the horse's hooves would find dry grass and set it alight.<br />
<br />
Then a straight shot across Western Karana, the horse's speed, unslowed from lack of turns, picked up so that the bandits hiding along the road only saw a streak of gold as she passed. One fired an arrow at their passage, but the arrow fell short far behind the rushing horse.<br />
<br />
Into Qeynos Hills, and a turn towards the city itself. Camille almost slipping from the horse's back as it turned suddenly. Only by leaning into the curve and swinging her sword arm straight back was she able to regain balance.<br />
<br />
Then up the cobblestone road to Qeynos.<br />
<br />
"Yapyapyapyap!" Fippy Darkpaw yelped, running ahead of them, charging towards the Qeynos gate, small gnoll brain oblivious that death was coming up the road behind him. "I claim Qeynos in the name of the Gn..."<br />
<br />
And then, in a mix of flaming hooves, burning gnoll hair, and broken bones, Fippy is run down by the horse and broken into a sad lump of twitching muscle on the road.<br />
<br />
"...olls." he finished lamely, the last of his breath leaving him with a deathrattle.<br />
<br />
Guards scattered as Camille and the horse plunged into their midst, taking corners at neckbreaking speed, Camille gripped Brimstone's mane so frantically she was surprised she hadn't torn the hair out of the horse's neck. Past big clock, the temple, the bank, to the docks they rode. The boat was in port, and Brimstone without care plunged up the ramp, crossing the boat, while passengers dove out of their way, some into the icy waters below, to avoid being trampled. The other side of the boat loomed quickly in front of them.<br />
<br />
"Brimstone..." Camille warned, knowing the crazy horse would ignore her. And it did, coming fast on the wooden railing on the far side of the boat, Brimstone bunched his muscles and leapt up and over the rail.<br />
<br />
I'll see you soon, River...Camille thought, closing her eyes as the sea rushed up toward her.<br />
<br />
Nothing. No jarring crash as they plunged into the sea, no cold icy grip as the water surrounded her, no gasp for breath as the ocean swallowed horse and rider.<br />
<br />
She opened her eyes slowly.<br />
<br />
They were galloping across the waves, white foam a foot under the horse's burning hooves, rushing across the water.<br />
<br />
"Where are you taking me??" Camille screamed over the roar of the sea.<br />
<br />
--VERY GOOD.-- Brimstone thought clearly to her, --I THOUGHT FOR SURE I WOULD LOSE YOU TURNING INTO THE CITY.--<br />
<br />
"Please, Brimstone," she begged, "I have had enough..."<br />
<br />
~~indeed, she has had enough~~ floated down an eerie female voice. ~~had i known you were going to attempt to kill her, i would have sent another more obedient servant~your time with the mortals has made you as bloodthirsty as they~~<br />
<br />
Brimstone's ears lay flat back against its head as the horse was chided, and the gallop reduced to a trot. Camille was afraid to untense her muscles, for fear she would fall off and pass out.<br />
<br />
~~to me, horse, and gently~~<br />
<br />
Brimstone neighed once. --YES, MISTRESS.--<br />
<br />
And with a shimmer of light, horse and rider disappeared.</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p></p>
